\begin_layout Subsection
Classical and Swarm-Based Metaheuristic Optimization Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Global optimization problems constitute a fundamental research topic across many scientific domains,
 as the need to determine optimal solutions arises in an increasing number of practical applications.
 The growing complexity of modern systems frequently leads to nonlinear,
 multimodal,
 and high-dimensional optimization problems,
 where classical deterministic approaches often fail to provide reliable solutions.
 Consequently,
 metaheuristic optimization algorithms have emerged as efficient alternatives due to their ability to explore large search spaces while avoiding local optima 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Genetic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Among the earliest and most widely adopted metaheuristic approaches are evolutionary algorithms,
 which simulate principles of biological evolution.
 Genetic Algorithms (GA) constitute one of the first successful population-based optimization techniques,
 employing mechanisms such as selection,
 crossover,
 and mutation to iteratively evolve candidate solutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Genetic,Genetic-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Differential Evolution (DE) was later introduced as an efficient optimization algorithm for continuous domains offering simple implementation and robust convergence behavior 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE,DE1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another important category of optimization methods is swarm intelligence,
 where search agents cooperate by simulating collective behaviors observed in natural systems.
 Representative algorithms include Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PSO,PSO-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Ant Colony Optimization (ACO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ACO,ACO-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Artificial Bee Colony (ABC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ABC,ABC-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which have demonstrated strong performance across a variety of optimization tasks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Recent Adaptive Metaheuristic Algorithms and Their Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In recent years,
 significant research attention has focused on the development of advanced metaheuristic algorithms aiming to improve search efficiency and convergence behavior.
 Various nature-inspired and adaptive optimization techniques have been proposed to enhance the balance between exploration and exploitation during the search process,
 which is widely regarded as a critical factor in metaheuristic performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Firefly,Firefly_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
 the Bat Algorithm (BA) which simulates the echolocation behavior of bats,
 has shown promising results in engineering optimization and global search applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bat,Bat_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additional modern swarm-based approaches include the Whale Optimization Algorithm (WOA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "woa,Woa1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Harris Hawks Optimization (HHO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hawks,Harris Hawks"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Aquila Optimizer (AO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aquila,Aquila_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Arithmetic Optimization Algorithm (AOA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AOA,AOA_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Magnificent Frigatebird Optimization Algorithm (MFO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MFO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Salp Swarm Algorithm (SSA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SSA,SSA_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These optimization algorithms seek to improve performance through adaptive movement operators,
 nonlinear parameter adjustment and dynamic search strategies.
 However,
 despite their promising effectiveness many recent metaheuristic methods continue to exhibit important limitations.
 In particular,
 they may suffer from premature convergence insufficient population diversity preservation and reduced robustness when applied to highly multimodal or large-scale optimization problems.
 Such limitations remain common challenges in modern metaheuristic optimization research and motivate the continuous development of improved and hybrid optimization strategies.
 To provide a clearer perspective the limitations of existing metaheuristic methods can be categorized into several main groups:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Exploration–exploitation imbalance,
 where algorithms fail to maintain an effective trade-off during the search process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Premature convergence,
 which leads to suboptimal solutions due to loss of population diversity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) Limited scalability,
 particularly in large-scale global optimization (LSGO) problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv) Insufficient parallel cooperation mechanisms,
 as many methods rely on sequential execution or weak interaction among subpopulations.
 These limitations highlight the need for more robust,
 scalable and cooperative optimization frameworks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Grey Wolf Optimization Variants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among swarm-based optimization algorithms,
 the GWO has attracted considerable attention due to its simplicity and effectiveness in solving continuous optimization problems.
 Inspired by the leadership hierarchy and cooperative hunting behavior of grey wolves,
 GWO models the interaction between 
