\begin_layout Subsection
A sensitivity analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sensitivity analysis is conducted to assess the impact of the propagation parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{P}$
\end_inset

 on the performance of the proposed algorithm using the Rosenbrock function (
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 = 25).
 The results expressed in terms of the number of function evaluations,
 are presented in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A sensitivity analysis_NR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A sensitivity analysis_NP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 As illustrated in Figure 8,
 the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 has a significant influence on the computational cost.
 In particular,
 increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 generally results in a higher number of function evaluations,
 although the relationship is not strictly monotonic.
 This behavior suggests that larger propagation ranges enhance exploration capabilities,
 at the expense of increased computational overhead due to redundant evaluations.
 In contrast Figure 9 shows that the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{P}$
\end_inset

 has a relatively limited effect on the number of function evaluations,
 as only minor variations are observed across different parameter settings.
 Overall moderate values of both parameters appear to provide an effective trade-off between convergence efficiency and computational cost.
 Furthermore the communication cost increases with higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{P}$
\end_inset

 since broader propagation mechanisms lead to more frequent interactions among agents.
 Notably the solution quality remains largely stable across different parameter configurations indicating that the proposed algorithm is robust with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 This observation suggests that these parameters primarily influence computational effort rather than the final optimization accuracy.
\end_layout

